Doctor: A licensed medical professional who diagnoses and treats illnesses, injuries, and medical conditions.
Nurse: A healthcare professional who provides patient care, administers treatments, and supports doctors in various medical settings.
Blood: The bodily fluid that circulates through the cardiovascular system, carrying oxygen, nutrients, and waste products.
Heart: The muscular organ that pumps blood throughout the body, providing oxygen and nutrients to cells.
Lungs: Organs responsible for breathing, where oxygen is taken in and carbon dioxide is expelled.
Teeth: Hard structures in the mouth used for biting and chewing food.
Brain: The central organ of the nervous system responsible for processing information, controlling bodily functions, and coordinating actions.
Bones: Rigid structures that make up the skeleton, providing support, protection, and mobility.
Cells: The basic unit of life that makes up all living organisms, carrying out various functions and processes.
Fever: An elevated body temperature often caused by an infection or illness.
Virus: A microscopic infectious agent that can cause various diseases in living organisms.
Germs: Microorganisms, including bacteria and viruses, that can cause disease or infection.
Health: The state of well-being and absence of disease or illness in a person.
Hygiene: Practices and behaviors aimed at maintaining cleanliness and preventing the spread of disease.
Sleep: A natural state of rest in which the body and mind rejuvenate.
Diet: The food and beverages a person regularly consumes.
Pulse: The rhythmic expansion and contraction of arteries as blood is pumped by the heart.
Stetho: A medical instrument used by healthcare professionals to listen to internal sounds of the body, such as the heartbeat and lung sounds.
Pain: An unpleasant sensory and emotional experience associated with tissue damage or injury.
Skin: The body's outermost protective layer, covering and safeguarding the underlying tissues and organs.
Wound: An injury to the body's tissues, typically involving a break in the skin.
Firstaid: Initial care and treatment provided for injuries or sudden illnesses before professional medical help is available.
Tooth: A hard structure in the mouth used for biting and chewing food.
Drugs: Substances used for medical treatment, often prescribed by a healthcare professional.
Bandage: A material used to cover and protect wounds or injuries.
Injury: Harm or damage to the body or a body part.
Allergy: A hypersensitive immune response to a substance that is typically harmless.
Vision: The ability to see and perceive the surrounding environment.
Plaque: A sticky film of bacteria on teeth that can lead to dental problems.
Muscle: Tissue that contracts and relaxes to facilitate movement and bodily functions.
Veins: Blood vessels that carry blood from various parts of the body back to the heart.
Immune: Related to the body's defense mechanisms against infections and diseases.
Sugar: A sweet carbohydrate often used as a source of energy.
Taste: The sensation experienced when eating or drinking, related to flavor.
Sound: Vibrations in the air that can be heard by the human ear.
Child: A young human being.
Swell: An abnormal increase in size or inflammation of a body part.
Throat: The passage at the back of the mouth connecting the mouth and the esophagus.
Cough: A sudden, forceful expulsion of air from the lungs to clear the throat or respiratory passages.
Anemia: A medical condition characterized by a deficiency of red blood cells or hemoglobin
Scales: Thin, flat structures often found on the skin or of fish, reptiles, and other animals.
Fluids: Substances that flow and can take the shape of their container.
Hiccups: Involuntary contractions of the diaphragm causing a sudden intake of air, followed by closure of the vocal cords, producing a distinctive sound.
Checkup: A medical examination or assessment to monitor a person's health.
Suture: Stitches used to close wounds or surgical incisions.
Cast: A rigid support or brace applied to a broken bone to promote healing and immobilize the injured area.